  "footnotes": [
    {
      "verse": 4,
      "letter": "",
      "content": "Jesus' command, “See that you tell no one,” reflects what scholars call the Messianic Secret—a recurring pattern in the Gospels where Jesus intentionally downplays public recognition of his miracles. This wasn't due to timidity, but strategic timing: premature fame could distort his mission, incite political unrest, or provoke opposition before the appointed hour. The instruction to show himself to the priest aligns with Leviticus 14, fulfilling the law and offering the healing as testimony—not spectacle. Jesus honors both covenant protocol and divine discretion."
    },
    {
      "verse": 12,
      "letter": "",
      "content": "The phrase “sons of the kingdom” refers to those—especially within Israel—who assumed their place in God's kingdom was guaranteed by ancestry or covenant identity, yet rejected Jesus as the Christ (cf. Matthew 21:43). The word “banished” translates the Greek <i>ekballō</i>, meaning “to throw out,” here signifying a solemn and final exclusion from God's presence. “Outer darkness” evokes a state of spiritual exile, cut off from the joy and light of the kingdom. The weeping and gnashing of teeth, repeated elsewhere (e.g. Matthew 13:42; 22:13), express profound regret and anguish. Jesus reverses expectations: those once assumed to be far off are welcomed in, while many presumed insiders are shut out—by their own unbelief, not divine injustice."
    },
    {
      "verse": 20,
      "letter": "",
      "content": "The phrase ‘Son of Man’ is a messianic title rooted in Daniel 7:13, where one like a son of man is given authority by God. Jesus uses this title to reveal both His humanity and divine appointment. His saying contrasts the comfort of worldly homes with His own path of rejection and pilgrimage, emphasizing the cost of true discipleship."
    },
    {
      "verse": 22,
      "letter": "",
      "content": "Jesus' command, “Let the dead bury their own dead,” is not a rejection of love or grief, but a call to radical spiritual urgency. The first “dead” refers to the spiritually unresponsive; the second, to the physically deceased. Though burial was a sacred duty in Jewish tradition, Jesus reveals that even the most honorable obligations must not delay obedience. His words expose the danger of postponing discipleship—even for reasons that seem noble."
    },
	{
      "verse": 29,
      "letter": "",
      "content": "“What have we to do with you?” from Greek phrase <i>ti hēmin kai soi</i> is a Hebrew idiom signaling hostility or distance (Judges 11:12; 1 Kings 17:18)."
    },
    {
      "verse": 34,
      "letter": "",
      "content": "The townspeople's request for Jesus to leave may seem surprising after witnessing a miraculous deliverance, but it reflects the tension between divine power and human fear. In casting out the demons, Jesus disrupted their economy—the loss of the pigs likely represented a major financial blow. But more than material loss, his presence exposed spiritual realities they were not prepared to face. Like in Luke 5:8, where Peter falls at Jesus' feet and says, “Depart from me, for I am a sinful man,” this moment reveals how holiness can provoke discomfort, especially when it confronts hidden darkness. Rather than rejoice over the liberation of the men, the town recoils at the cost and the presence of one whose authority they could not control."
    }
  ]
